				<h1 style="color: #F2711C; font-family: Lobster Two" id="What">What is Ido?</h1>
				<div class="ui fitted divider"></div>
				<p>Ido is a reform of Esperanto. Ido fixes alot of problems, add new features, makes it more recognizable and makes it more beautiful and neutral-looking!</p>
				<p>Here is some features that where changed in Ido:</p>
				<div class="ui bulleted list">
					<div class="item">Gender neutrality - Ido does not expect any noun to be either male or female. Instead is every noun (except a hand-full, <a href="#Neutrality" style="color: #F2711C">see below</a>) neutral, and can be changed with either a male of female suffix.</div>
					<div class="item">No extra letters - Ido doesn’t add its own letters, in fact, Ido has taken the whole English alphabet, without changes.</div>
					<div class="item">Better root selection - Ido has a more neat system for choosing roots (<a href="#Vocabulary" style="color: #F2711C">see below</a>).</div>
					<div class="item">Less ancient words - Ido gets rid of all the unnecessary Ancient Greek roots, and a lot of Latin. While instead grab Latin roots where the languages don’t agree with each other.</div>
					<div class="item">100% logical - Ido was given a huge logical boost (<a href="#Logical" style="color: #F2711C">see below</a>).</div>
				</div>
				<img src="havaji/imaji/idoflago.png">
			</div>
			<div class="ui orange stacked segment">
				<h1 style="color: #F2711C; font-family: Lobster Two" id="History">How did Ido come to be?</h1>
				<div class="ui fitted divider"></div>
				<h3>Age of Volapük</h3>
				<p>In 1879 came Volapük. The first man-made language that became big and popular. As it being the first huge create language, had it a lot of problems, and being overly complicated (than what it actually could be). Because of this, a lot of people started experimenting with languages themselves, but non got any more popular. After a short while, this toned down, and everyone just went with Volapük. Around 1890, things started to derail, people started arguing, and people started to create their own venison of Volapük. It was around that time, that people started leaving Volapük, and for the next 10-20, the amount of speakers of Volapük became but a hand-full. While people where arguing, and creating their own languages, stepped Zamenhof forward.</p>
				<h3>Esperanto sneaked in</h3>
				<p> Being a polyglot, and living in Poland, a bad place in the end of the 19-century. Since the Volapükian movement had crashed, he saw he could step in, and take over with his own language (as oppose to the other, newer variants of Volapük), he called it "Lingwe universala" (The Universal Language). Later, Zamenhof dropped most uses of "w", and the name was "Lingve internacia" (The International Language). After releasing his first book called "Lingve internacia", people started calling the language "Esperanto" (the nickname Zamenhof used for himself), instead of the accusal name. Esperanto was released at the perfect time, as almost every Volapükian that was left, jumped to Esperanto. It didn't take long before people started arguing over Esperanto, as it itself wasen't perfect (though better then Volapük). People started experimenting with creating their version of Esperanto (called "Esperantido", meaning "offspring of Esperanto"). It didn't take long, before Zamenhof became overwhelmed, and decided to do his own reform, instead of people making their own. The following year constructed Zamenhof his own, new Esperanto (2.0), but when he presented it to his followers, unexpectedly, the majority didn't take the changes Zamenhof made, instead using protesting and using the previous Esperanto (1.0). Zamenhof tried, and even though a lot took the changes, the majority kept using the previous. Zamenhof gave up, and the reform died.In the beginning of the 20-century, more auxiliary languages was made, and a group of people decided to open a Delegation to try to gather people to one language, instead of there being a lot of small different languages. The Delegation was made of several different people from several different countries, and most of them was professors or different high ranking professions. After looking at the different choices, and Esperanto being the "most perfect" of the bunch, someone within the group decided to propose to make a new language, based upon Esperanto. He (unknown who) wrote down several features he found immediately, but more could be changed with time. The group decided to take the offer, and the unknown member stepped forward, being Louis de Beaufront, the linguist in the group. He named the project: "Ido.</p>
				<h3>Ido was born</h3>
				<p>Louis de Beaufront, being a linguist, had more knowledge in language making, and could create a "more perfect" Esperanto. Zamenhof got outraged of this proposal, and forbid them from using the name "Esperanto" for the language. Under the following years, created the Delegation Ido. The Delegation went through several different suggestions, and the ones that wanted, voted on what they wanted. After the language was finished, the a union was created, calling themselves "Uniono di la Amiki di la Linguo Internaciona" (The Union of Friends of the International Language). Ido lived, and continued to developed, new features was proposed, and old was changed. Ido has lived for 108 years (in 2015).</p>
			</div>
			<div class="ui orange stacked segment">
				<h1 style="color: #F2711C; font-family: Lobster Two" id="Neutrality">Ido has total gender neutrality!</h1>
				<div class="ui fitted divider"></div>
				<p>Ido is probably the only language in the world that has total, 100% genderqueer, or in other words; no bias towards either sex!</p>
				<p>Ido has a few words that are male or female only, but those are less then ten, so don't worry!</p>
				<table class="ui orange definition striped table">
