				<h1 style="color: #F2711C; font-family: Lobster Two" id="Vocabulary">How and where does Ido get it's vocabulary?</h1>
				<div class="ui fitted divider"></div>
				<p>Idos number 1 role, was to be a universal second language, never to replace the natural languages; but to be there when needed! Because of that, all of the different maker of Ido held the idea, that the language should be as easy to learn for the most amount of people as possible. Now, this is a little bit different than the language Ido grew out of, has bit of a different aim. Even so, Ido tries to keep a few souvenirs from its grandfather (in Ido, Esperanto is known as <i>l'avo</i>, translating to either the grandfather or the grandmother). So in Ido, six languages was choosen,</p>
				<p>A case of where Ido saw flaw in Esperanto, is for an example the word for <i>page</i>. In Esperanto the word for page is <i>paĝo - pagho - pagxo</i>. The Esperanto took its word from English and French word <i>page</i> (English itself got it from French). To full fill the role of <i>as easy as possible for the most amount of people as possible</i>, Ido replaced it with <i>pagino</i>. Compare to the table below.</p>
